<strong>Kodak</strong><br>
<br>
A recent positive example was Kodak. After management announced a prospective ‘Kodakcoin’ the stock jumped nearly fourfold.<br>
<br>
This is a textbook case of why shorting bankrupt companies in their final 1-2 years is such a dicey proposition. A 2-3% short position made before the announcement would have been extraordinarily painful.<br>
<br>
However, <em>after</em> a short squeeze has taken place, there are often good trading opportunities. Every time the share price rises during a squeeze, additional shorts were forced to buy-back shares, causing a new high and more forced buying.<br>
<br>
Eventually the squeeze subsides and the price falls – this is the point that we entered Kodak.<br>
<br>
Such trades also have a clear stop loss – if the stock reaches new highs, that indicates the forced buying has more room to run.  We held the position for 8 days, which is just as well, as at one point the cost to hold this position was quoted at >200% annualized.<br>
<br>
We had the conviction to enter a position slightly larger than 4% - which is a size we would only reach in rare situations for brief periods of time, and even then, only when the trade contributes to the portfolio more broadly. At the end of January, this was a very welcome addition to our portfolio, and we closed our position for a profit of 35%.<br>
